{
  "text": "Plain X-ray has been used for the diagnosis of osteomyelitis; however, it is not suitable for early diagnosis because the appearance of bone destruction and periosteal reaction occurs 7-14 days after onset [CITATION_1] . A definitive diagnosis of pubic osteomyelitis is typically made based on an imaging examination. CT and MRI are useful for the definitive diagnosis for pubic osteomyelitis. The sensitivity and specificity of MRI for pubic osteomyelitis is 97% and 94%, respectively [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . MRI is suitable for the evaluation of soft tissues, and it can clearly distinguish between normal and infected bone marrow. Therefore, MRI can capture the specific traits of pubic osteomyelitis, such as edematous change and the effect on bone marrow. MRI is also superior in evaluating the extent of inflammation or to detect abscess formation [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [14] . If pubic osteomyelitis is clinically suspected, CT and MRI should be considered",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "45001567",
    "[CITATION_2]": "15961643",
